sentences: Talvin Wayne Cochran (May 10, 1939 – November 21, 2017) was an American soul singer, known for his outlandish outfits and white pompadour hairstyle.
Cochran is best known today for writing the song "Last Kiss", which he performed with the C.C. Riders.
Talvin Wayne Cochran was born on May 10, 1939, in Thomaston, Georgia, to Talvin A. Cochran, a cotton mill worker, and the former Mini Lee Starley, who came from a farming family.

Cochran also recorded a "live" album (actually a "live in the studio" record) for King sometime between 1967 and 1969, but released in 2014 and included in an Ace Records compilation Goin' Back to Miami: The Soul Sides 1965-1970.

Cochran recorded a final album, titled Cochran, for Epic Records in 1972, then toured and made television appearances.
He died on November 21, 2017 in Miramar, Florida, from cancer at the age of 78.
Cochran is best known today for writing the song "Last Kiss", which he performed with the C.C. Riders.
Although it was not a success for him, contemporary covers by J. Frank Wilson and the Cavaliers in 1964, Wednesday in 1974, and a much later take by Pearl Jam became hits.

Cochran and his revue also influenced Dan Aykroyd and John Belushi's Blues Brothers musical venture; Cochran is referenced in the 1980 film The Blues Brothers and a cover of his song "Going Back to Miami" is featured on the live album Made in America.
Appeared and sang in the 1970 movie C.C. and Company as himself.

The movie trailer, featuring a scene with Cochran and his band The C.C. Riders performing the song "I Can't Turn You Loose", was later used in the 2019 Quentin Tarantino movie Once Upon a Time in Hollywood.
On June 25, 2019, The New York Times listed Wayne Cochran among hundreds of artists whose material was destroyed in the 2008 Universal fire.
